post_text: Today, the Krewe of Themis, comprised of former members of the Krewe of Nyx, delivered monetary donations to #BTW, #FDHS and #KIPPLeadership. This donation covered any financial support our schools were expecting as part of our participation in the Krewe of Nyx. In June, we withdrew our bands and auxiliary units from marching in the Krewe of Nyx’s parades after the Krewe captain’s insensitive comments about the #BlackLivesMatter movement. We are thankful for this donation as we continue to stand with the black community in this fight for social justice. Thank you, #KreweOfThemis! #BlackLivesMatter

post_text: Today, we remember the tragedy of Hurricane Katrina, 15 years ago. Our first KIPP school was only open for a month before the storm made landfall. Words cannot capture the pain and devastation that was experienced by so many. Yet, as a city and a community we have grown stronger together. Through our belief in resilience, we have remained committed to the young people of this great city. KNOS continues to work with all New Orleanians to create unlimited opportunities for every student in New Orleans.

Estimadas familias de KNOS:

Debido a la amenaza anticipada del clima tropical que se acerca esta semana, las Escuelas Públicas de NOLA han cancelado toda la instrucción virtual para el lunes 24 y martes 25 de agosto. Todos los campus y edificios de las escuelas KIPP New Orleans estarán cerrados los lunes y martes. La distribución de comidas también se cancelará mañana y las condiciones climáticas pendientes se reanudarán el miércoles 26 de agosto de 8 a.m. a 11 a.m. Continuaremos monitoreando el clima durante toda la semana y le informaremos sobre los días adicionales de cierre de la escuela. Nuestro plan actual es reanudar la instrucción virtual el miércoles. Le informaremos si eso cambia.

post_text:
Dear KNOS Families:

Due to the anticipated threat of tropical weather approaching this week, NOLA Public Schools has cancelled all virtual instruction for Monday, August 24 and Tuesday, August 25. All KIPP New Orleans Schools campuses and buildings will be closed Monday and Tuesday. Meal distribution will also be cancelled tomorrow and pending weather conditions will resume on Wednesday, August 26 from 8 a.m. to 11 a.m. We will continue to monitor weather throughout the week and inform you of any additional school closure days. Our current plan is to resume virtual instruction on Wednesday. We will let you know if that changes.

Continue to check your email and all KNOS social media pages for updated information. Please be safe and reach out to your school if you have any questions.

Dear KNOS Families:

Meal distribution will also be cancelled tomorrow and pending weather conditions will resume on Wednesday, August 26 from 8 a.m. to 11 a.m. We will continue to monitor weather throughout the week and inform you of any additional school closure days. Our current plan is to resume virtual instruction on Wednesday. We will let you know if that changes.

Continue to check your email and all KNOS social media pages for updated information. Please be safe and reach out to your school if you have any questions.

post_text: Since 2010, we have partnered with The Bon Vivants to improve school campuses across our network. In 2010, they held their first volunteer day at KIPP with 15 volunteers and gave a $1500 donation. Today, they have more than quadrupled their impact by providing over 100 volunteers each year and have worked on 6 of our 9 campuses for a combined total of 6000+ hours of service! The Bon Vivants have contributed over $220K to #KNOS over the years. Unfortunately this year, due to COVID-19, we are unable to have our annual volunteer day. Despite this, we are still grateful and thankful for your partnership! Thank you, The Bon Vivants, for your hard work & dedication to our students and schools. We sincerely appreciate you as part of our team and family! #Impact #pignpunch #totc #volunteerday

As we know, COVID-19 has dramatically impacted our world and the way we engage with each other. Though COVID-19 may have changed our engagement norms, our beliefs have not and will not change; we will continue to be true to that. With that, we have begun planning for the beginning of the school year and reopening our schools on August 10, 2020 based on the guidance of the LDOE, OPSB and our city’s health officials!

For more information, please visit kippneworleans.org/reopening.

post_text: Today, June 19, 2020, is a day of honor, engagement & action across our region in observance of #Juneteenth. Therefore, our offices and schools will be closed today & we will recognize Juneteenth as an annual holiday every year. We will use this time to celebrate African-American freedom and continue the process of self-development. #KNOS joins the African-American community in actively working to end systematic racism in this country. #BlackLivesMatter

post_text:
We are proud to announce that our 2020 graduates Johana Murcia-Mendez (FDHS), Keyli Motino-Chirinos (BTW) and Hector Vargas (BTW) have been recognized as 2019-2020 State Seal of Biliteracy Scholars. This prestigious award is given to high school graduates who demonstrate a high level of proficiency in the four domains of English, and another language. At KNOS, we understand the value of diversity & cultural heritage and we are elated that our students are being recognized for this great honor! Congratulations, scholars!

-

Estamos orgullosos de anunciar que nuestros graduados de 2020 Johana Murcia-Méndez (FDHS), Keyli Motino-Chirinos (BTW) y Héctor Vargas (BTW) han sido reconocidos como Sello Estatal de Becarios de Bialfabetismo. Este prestigioso premio se otorga a los graduados de secundaria que demuestran un alto nivel de competencia en los cuatro dominios del inglés y otro idioma.
En KNOS, entendemos el valor de la diversidad y el patrimonio cultural y estamos eufóricos de que nuestros estudiantes están siendo reconocidos por este gran honor! ¡Felicidades, becarios!

post_text: “We engage in this work so that our students are able to live in a world that is more just, one in which the institutional racism that plagues this country has been dismantled. We must work harder and smarter to create an equitable education for our students. And we must support our students and community to heal, to demand justice, and to keep their dreams alive and reachable.” - #KNOS CEO Rhonda Kalifey-Aluise #BlackLivesMatter #GeorgeFloyd #AhmaudArbery #BreonnaTaylor

post_text: We’re excited to partner with the S&WB of New Orleans to kick off American Water Works Association’s Drinking Water Week! This week, water utilities across the country come together to recognize the vital role water plays in our daily lives. To celebrate, we’re hosting a children’s artwork contest. The winner will receive a tour of our Carrollton Water Plant, where the water you use every day is purified! The tour will be scheduled after social distancing measures are lifted. Send your drawings to ‪media@swbno.org‬ by ‪May 11‬

post_text: Our #KCCA teacher volunteers, in partnership with Delgado Fab Lab, have joined the fight against Covid-19 by creating Personal Protection Equipment (PPE) for medical workers on the front lines! Designs such 3d printed face masks, strap extenders for n95 face masks, face shields to protect from droplets, aerosol boxes to safely work on patients and ventilator splitters were all created by the Makers team. So far, they have shipped hundreds of assembled masks & face shields to hospitals in need! Special thanks to the our #KCCA Makers team and Delgado Fab Lab for your support in fighting this pandemic.

post_text: Calling all high school educators! Join the KIPP New Orleans Team and Family at Booker T. Washington High School, John F. Kennedy High School, and Frederick A. Douglass High School, and help us build a better tomorrow in the Big Easy! As one of the strongest charter management organizations in the city, we offer exceptional professional development opportunities that drive your effectiveness and impact in the classroom. Safe, structured, nurturing school communities focus on academic and character growth, and our KIPP Through College program supports our vision that all students will live a life filled with opportunity. With 3 years of experience, a KNOS teacher is paid $3,500 more than the citywide average. What are you waiting for? Apply to KIPP New Orleans Schools today! https://kippcareers.secure.force.com/jobboard?site=new%20orleans

post_text: This semester, scholars from #BTW & #FDHS participated in our second annual Black Lives Matter writing competition. In 1962, Malcom X claimed, “The most disrespected person in America is the black woman.” Scholars submitted fantastic pieces of work expressing their understanding and beliefs around this statement as it relates to today’s society. We selected 10 winners of this competition and they will receive an all expense paid trip to Washington D.C.! The trip was scheduled for this semester, however due to COVID-19, we have rescheduled the trip for this upcoming fall. Congratulations to all of our winners and they will be announced at 12pm each day this upcoming Monday - Friday (April 20-24).

post_text:
Our #KCCA and #KNOS family held a drive in memorial to honor the legacy of our friend, Walter Harris, Jr. Team members created memorial signage & wrote their favorite memories of Mr. Harris on index cards that were presented to his family. Mr. Harris was such a warm, friendly, insightful person & today’s memorial expressed how much we loved him and how much he impacted our lives. We will continue to support the Harris family and each other during this difficult time. #WaltersArmy

post_text: Our KIPP New Orleans Schools community is deeply saddened by the loss of our beloved KIPP Central City Academy Assistant Principal Walter Harris. Having been with us for 6 years, Mr. Harris was a pillar in our community. He was an incredible educator, father, husband and friend. His commitment to education and his support of fellow staff members, students and families was unwavering. He always put others first and showed love through his actions. His impact will echo through our hearts and the halls of KCCA forever. He was a source of wisdom and knowledge and a guide and mentor to all. This is an incredible loss for our community; we ask everyone to support the Harris family and one another with love and understanding.

Reminder🚨

Schedule Update: In an effort to better serve and protect the health of students, families, food service providers and staff at community feeding sites, NOLA Public Schools and their partners are condensing the weekly schedule at the Citywide Feeding Program sites by providing multiple days of meals during specific daily time frames.
•
‪Thursday March 26: M‬eals will be served for both Thursday and Friday. Service Hours: 9 am – 12 pm‬.
•
‪Friday, March 27th: ‬Community Feeding Sites will NOT be open ‪on Friday, March 27.‬
•
‪Starting March 30th and Moving Forward:‬
* Every Monday we will provide meals for 2 days.
* Every Wednesday we will provide meals for 3 days.
* Moving forward Community Feeding sites will NOT be open on Tuesday, Thursday or Friday.
* Service Hours: remain the same, ‪9 am – 12 pm‬.
For more, please visit nolapublicschools.com/covid19/nutrition

post_text: Today, New Orleans Public Schools announced that all Orleans Parish schools will be closed for the next four weeks due to confirmed cases of Coronavirus (COVID-19) in our city/state. The safety and health of our students and staff are our number one priority. We want to stress that this is being done out of an abundance of caution. We take this threat seriously and must do our part as a community to slow the spread of this virus. For more information and updates, please visit kippneworleans.org/coronavirusupdates or cdc.gov/coronavirus.

post_text: We have been working closely with NOLA Public Schools and City Officials to stay up to date on necessary steps our schools, staff and families must take regarding the coronavirus outbreak. We take this threat seriously and want to make sure everyone has the information to maintain health and safety. We realize that with this moment comes fear and uncertainty. We are confident that we will weather this well and all do our part to help our community slow the spread of this virus so that healthcare workers can do the critical work of taking care of those in need. With that in mind, we are sharing important information that can be found at kippneworleans.org/cornonavirusupdates. We encourage you to reach out to your school or coronavirus@kippneworleans.org if you have any questions.

post_text: PLEASE REPOST AND SHARE – Last night, there was a Facebook post falsely identifying a KIPP principal as supporting a Krewe of Nyx rider spitting on black males along the parade route. The behavior mentioned in the post does not reflect what KIPP New Orleans Schools stands for; none of our KIPP New Orleans Schools principals rode in the Nyx parade last night and to our knowledge none of our staff members were on the float mentioned in the post. We have reached out to the person that originally posted the message to find out more information, and we are still waiting for a reply. One of our core beliefs is centered around equity and recognizing the strength of diversity and inclusivity; we would never support or condone this absolutely deplorable behavior and we do not wish this experience on anyone. #Truth #Inclusivity

post_text: It’s #STEMcember at KIPP Morial! Science Coach Ms. Biermann is working with scholars as they build robots and learn how states of matter move! Scholars even moved robots through mazes by using advanced coding sequences. #KNOS middle schools are the only schools in the city that build coding and robotics into the core science curriculum! Research tells us that exposure to Computer Science fields in K-12 matters - 98% of Computer Science majors report having been exposed to Computer Science prior to college. By offering scholars access to these programs now, they are more likely to take advantage of these lucrative careers in the future! Go #KIPPsters! 🤖

Our teachers are not only being recognized by us but across the world! Sending a special shout out to KIPP: Ernest N. "Dutch" Morial School Special Education teacher Ms. Lauren Jewett! Ms. Jewett is a National Board Certified Teacher and has been selected as one of 25 Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development (ASCD) Emerging Leaders in the 2019 cohort! Additionally, she was selected as one of the 13 Understood Teacher Fellows through the Understood.Org organization! Congratulations, Lauren; we look forward to the lessons you will bring to your students and school community!

post_text: It was an amazing morning at Booker T. Washington High School as we celebrated the official Ribbon Cutting Ceremony! BTW was first opened in 1942 and was the first secondary high school built in NOLA specifically to educate African American 9th-12th grade students. BTW was attended by some of the most prominent and influential leaders in NOLA until its closure in 2004. On August 8, 2019, after a 15 year absence, BTW, under the operation of KIPP New Orleans Schools, reopened at its original location. This will be the first year BTW will graduate a senior class since 2004! The new building, designed by Hewitt and Washington Architects, is 198,873 square feet and accommodates grades 9th-12th. The new building includes 52 classrooms, a brand-new media center, and breathtaking gymnasium! Welcome back to the #OriginalLionsDen!
